# These values reflect the stage information , but are all missing in Pancancer Atlas data 
# 'PATH_M_STAGE','PATH_N_STAGE','AJCC_PATHOLOGIC_TUMOR_STAGE', 'PATH_T_STAGE'
choose_columns <- c('PATIENT_ID', 'SUBTYPE', 'AGE','SEX', 'RACE', 
                    'OS_STATUS','OS_MONTHS', "DFS_MONTHS","DFS_STATUS")

patient_df_selected = patient_df[,choose_columns]

#################################################################
# Add age group
#################################################################

patient_df_selected %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = AGE)) + geom_histogram(bins = 40)
## Warning: Removed 102 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).

patient_df_selected$Age_Group <- cut(patient_df_selected$AGE, 
    breaks = c(-Inf, 40,50,60,70,80,Inf), 
    labels = c("0-39 years","40-49 years","50-59 years","60-69 years","70-79 years","80+ years"),
    right = FALSE)

UCSC Xena - GDC database have phenotype.tsv with following information

  • submitter_id : TCGA-13-1407
  • submitter_id.samples : TCGA-30-1857-01A
  • clinical_stage : Stage IIIC, Stage IIC,
  • neoplasm_histologic_grade : G3, G2,
  • race.demographic : white, not reported,
  • vital_status.demographic : Alive, Dead

Function: Clean table by removing missing value and empty cells in a given column

# data filteration (missing value and empty cells)
clean_cols <- function(df, target){
  # this function aims to remove Na and empty cells in a given column
  df_omit <- df[!is.na(df[[target]]), ]
  empty_rows <- !nzchar(trimws(df_omit[[target]]))
  df_omit <- df_omit[!empty_rows, ]
  return(df_omit)
}
